      <h1>Ana de Armas All Movies List</h1>
      <p class="subtitle">A comprehensive journey through the diverse and critically acclaimed filmography of Ana de Armas.</p>
    </div>

    <section class="content-section">
      <p>Ana de Armas has rapidly become one of the most compelling and sought-after actresses in modern cinema. From her early beginnings in Cuban and Spanish television to becoming a central figure in massive Hollywood franchises, tracking the <strong>Ana de Armas all movies list</strong> is akin to watching a masterclass in career evolution. Her filmography isn't just a list of credits; it's a testament to her versatility, taking her from psychological thrillers to high-octane action and deeply emotional biographical dramas.</p>

      <p>Understanding her body of work gives us insight into how international talent transitions into the Hollywood system. Unlike many actors who find a niche and stay there, de Armas has deliberately chosen roles that challenge both her and the audience's perception of her capabilities. Whether she's navigating the complex moral landscape of a futuristic Los Angeles or stealing scenes in a blockbuster spy thriller, her presence is undeniably magnetic.</p>

      <h2>The Early Years: Cuban and Spanish Cinema</h2>
      <p>Before the world knew her name, Ana de Armas was honing her craft in Spanish-language cinema. Her debut leading role came in the 2006 romantic drama <em>Una rosa de Francia</em>. This period was crucial for developing the foundational acting skills she would later rely on in high-pressure Hollywood sets. Moving to Madrid at 18, she starred in the immensely popular teen drama series <em>El Internado</em> (The Boarding School) from 2007 to 2010. This show was a cultural phenomenon in Spain and proved she could handle long-form storytelling and complex character arcs.</p>

      <p>These formative years are essential when looking at the complete Ana de Armas all movies list. They show a young actor willing to take risks and relocate her entire life to pursue her art. The discipline learned on Spanish television—tight schedules, demanding emotional scenes, and building an ensemble dynamic—served as the perfect training ground for the demanding roles she would later tackle.</p>

      <div class="callout">
        <strong>The Language Barrier:</strong> When Ana de Armas moved to Los Angeles in 2014, she spoke very little English. For her early English-speaking roles, such as in <em>Knock Knock</em> and <em>War Dogs</em>, she learned her lines phonetically, memorizing the sounds rather than fully understanding every word—a remarkable feat of dedication and memory.
      </div>

      <h2>The Hollywood Breakthrough: Sci-Fi and Mystery</h2>
      <p>The transition to Hollywood is notoriously difficult, but Ana de Armas navigated it with a series of strategic and impactful roles. After supporting parts in films like <em>Knock Knock</em> (2015) alongside Keanu Reeves, and the comedy-crime film <em>War Dogs</em> (2016), she landed a role that would shift the trajectory of her career entirely.</p>

      <p>In 2017, she starred as Joi, a holographic AI companion, in Denis Villeneuve's visually stunning <em>Blade Runner 2049</em>. This role required a delicate balance of artificiality and profound, albeit simulated, human emotion. It proved she could hold her own alongside industry veterans like Ryan Gosling and Harrison Ford in a high-stakes, big-budget environment.</p>

      <p>However, it was Rian Johnson's 2019 whodunit <em>Knives Out</em> that truly cemented her status as a leading lady. Playing Marta Cabrera, a nurse caught in the middle of a wealthy family's dysfunction and a murder investigation, she became the emotional core of the film. Her performance was nuanced, empathetic, and universally praised, earning her a Golden Globe nomination for Best Actress in a Motion Picture – Comedy or Musical.</p>

      <h2>Action Star and Biographical Drama</h2>
      <p>If <em>Knives Out</em> proved her dramatic chops, her next major roles demonstrated an astonishing range. In 2021, she reunited with her <em>Knives Out</em> co-star Daniel Craig in the James Bond film <em>No Time to Die</em>. Playing Paloma, a vivacious and highly capable CIA agent, she stole the show in a relatively short amount of screen time. The role required intensive physical training and choreography, proving her viability as an action star.</p>

      <p>This action prowess was further highlighted in films like <em>The Gray Man</em> (2022) and led to her securing the lead role in <em>Ballerina</em>, a highly anticipated spinoff in the expansive John Wick universe, expanding the lore established by characters like those seen in <a href="/the-terminal-list">The Terminal List</a>.</p>

      <p>Simultaneously, she took on perhaps her most challenging role to date: portraying Marilyn Monroe in Andrew Dominik's psychological biographical drama <em>Blonde</em> (2022). The film itself was highly polarizing, but de Armas's raw, vulnerable, and deeply committed performance was widely celebrated. She captured the agonizing duality of Norma Jeane Mortenson and the public persona of Marilyn Monroe, earning an Academy Award nomination for Best Actress—making history as the first Cuban woman to be nominated in that category.</p>

      <h2>Why Her Filmography Matters</h2>
      <p>The Ana de Armas all movies list is significant for several reasons. First, it represents a breakdown of traditional Hollywood casting barriers. As a Latina actress, she has consistently secured roles that were not explicitly written for a specific ethnicity, proving that talent and screen presence can transcend outdated industry norms.</p>

      <p>Second, her career trajectory is a blueprint for strategic role selection. By alternating between prestige dramas, independent films, and massive franchises, she has avoided typecasting. She is as believable as a vulnerable nurse as she is a lethal assassin or a tragic Hollywood icon. This versatility ensures her longevity in an industry that often discards actors who fail to evolve.</p>

      <p>Furthermore, her global appeal demonstrates the increasingly international nature of modern cinema. Actors are no longer confined to their regional markets; true stars can draw audiences worldwide, and Ana de Armas is a prime example of this global cinematic language.</p>

      <div class="card">
        <h3>Key Milestones in the Ana de Armas Movies List</h3>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>2006:</strong> Feature film debut in <em>Una rosa de Francia</em>.</li>
          <li><strong>2015:</strong> First English-speaking role in <em>Knock Knock</em>.</li>
          <li><strong>2017:</strong> Breakout sci-fi role in <em>Blade Runner 2049</em>.</li>
          <li><strong>2019:</strong> Golden Globe-nominated performance in <em>Knives Out</em>.</li>
          <li><strong>2021:</strong> Iconic action sequence in James Bond's <em>No Time to Die</em>.</li>
          <li><strong>2022:</strong> Historic Academy Award nomination for <em>Blonde</em>.</li>
          <li><strong>2025:</strong> Leading the action franchise spinoff <em>Ballerina</em>.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <p>Looking at the Ana de Armas all movies list, it is clear that we are witnessing the prime of one of this generation's most dynamic actors. Her commitment to character, combined with an undeniable on-screen charisma, suggests that her most defining roles may still be ahead of her.</p>

    </section>

    <section class="faq-section">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <details>
        <summary>What is the complete Ana de Armas movies list?</summary>
        <p>The complete Ana de Armas movies list includes over 30 films. Her notable Spanish-language films include <em>Una rosa de Francia</em> and <em>Por un puñado de besos</em>. Her Hollywood career features hits like <em>Knock Knock</em>, <em>War Dogs</em>, <em>Blade Runner 2049</em>, <em>Knives Out</em>, <em>No Time to Die</em>, <em>Deep Water</em>, <em>The Gray Man</em>, <em>Blonde</em>, <em>Ghosted</em>, and <em>Ballerina</em>.</p>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary>What was Ana de Armas's breakout movie?</summary>
        <p>While <em>Blade Runner 2049</em> (2017) introduced her to a massive global audience, her true Hollywood breakout movie was Rian Johnson's <em>Knives Out</em> (2019). Playing the lead role of Marta Cabrera, she earned widespread critical acclaim and a Golden Globe nomination, proving she could carry a major ensemble film.</p>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary>Is Ana de Armas in a James Bond movie?</summary>
        <p>Yes, Ana de Armas starred in the 25th James Bond film, <em>No Time to Die</em> (2021). She played Paloma, a vibrant and deadly CIA agent operating in Cuba who assists James Bond (Daniel Craig). Despite her relatively short screen time, her performance was widely considered one of the highlights of the movie.</p>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary>Did Ana de Armas win an Oscar for Blonde?</summary>
        <p>Ana de Armas did not win the Oscar, but she was nominated for the Academy Award for Best Actress for her portrayal of Marilyn Monroe in the 2022 film <em>Blonde</em>. This was a historic nomination, as she became the first Cuban woman ever to be nominated in the Best Actress category.</p>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary>What are the best movies with Ana de Armas?</summary>
        <p>Based on critical reception and audience popularity, the best movies featuring Ana de Armas include <em>Knives Out</em> (a brilliant modern whodunit), <em>Blade Runner 2049</em> (a visually stunning sci-fi masterpiece), <em>No Time to Die</em> (a thrilling spy blockbuster), and <em>Blonde</em> (a challenging and polarizing biographical drama). Her upcoming role in <em>Ballerina</em> is also highly anticipated.</p>
      </details>
